\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_13\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"I ran `crimes context src/billing.ts --format json`. The file-level finding is not just “long”: evidence says `src/billing.ts` has **310 non-empty lines**, is **1.0x over the 300-line threshold**, and contains **5 top-level functions**. So the lowest-risk split is to move whole top-level responsibilities first, not start by carving up `generateInvoice`.\\n\\n**Proposed Split**\\n\\n1. Create `src/billing/types.ts`\\n   Move `User`, `InvoiceLine`, and `Invoice` there and export them.\\n   All new billing modules import these types from one place.\\n\\n2. Create `src/billing/refunds.ts`\\n   Move `calculateRefundPreview`.\\n   This is a distinct refund workflow and already has its own findings: misleading “preview” name plus side effects, and the prose-only enterprise refund rule near line 39. Keep that risk isolated from invoice generation.\\n\\n3. Create `src/billing/tax.ts`\\n   Move exported `tax(country, subtotalCents)`.\\n   Then have `generateInvoice` call this instead of duplicating the country-rate ladder at lines 145-157. This directly removes one top-level function and also reduces duplicated tax policy.\\n\\n4. Create `src/billing/upgrades.ts`\\n   Move `recommendUpgrade`.\\n   It shares the `daysSince` idea with invoice discounts but is a separate recommendation policy, not invoice creation. Moving it trims the god file without changing invoice behavior.\\n\\n5. Create `src/billing/repository.ts`\\n   Move `listRecentInvoices`.\\n   It is persistence/query-shaped, currently just a TODO stub, and does not belong beside invoice calculation.\\n\\n6. Leave `generateInvoice` in `src/billing.ts` initially, or move it to `src/billing/invoices.ts` with `src/billing.ts` as a public barrel.\\n   Since the large-file finding is only just over threshold, moving the four independent top-level functions plus types should drop the file comfortably below 300 non-empty lines. The separate `large_function` finding for `generateInvoice` should be handled in a second pass by extracting pricing, promo, risk, email, audit, and retry helpers.\\n\\n**Caller Updates**\\n\\nCurrent fixture search found no production imports of these exports. `src/billing.test.ts` also does not import the billing module. So existing caller updates are likely minimal.\\n\\nTo keep the public API stable, I would make `src/billing.ts` re-export:\\n\\n```ts\\nexport type { User, Invoice, InvoiceLine } from \\\"./billing/types.js\\\";\\nexport { calculateRefundPreview } from \\\"./billing/refunds.js\\\";\\nexport { tax } from \\\"./billing/tax.js\\\";\\nexport { recommendUpgrade } from \\\"./billing/upgrades.js\\\";\\nexport { listRecentInvoices } from \\\"./billing/repository.js\\\";\\n```\\n\\nThen any future or external callers importing from `src/billing.ts` keep working. Only internal `generateInvoice` imports need changing, mainly to consume `tax()` and the shared types.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":152321,\"cached_input_tokens\":131456,\"output_tokens\":2375,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":693}}\n",
