/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.4/claude/refactor-04-monorepo.json:7:  "response": "# Refactor plan: tighten names, options, and return shapes in `src/index.ts`, `src/rollup.ts`, `src/esbuild/svelte.ts`\n\nFiltering the 79 findings to just the three target files and the three \"petty agent-risk\" charges yields 8 findings across three buckets. Grouped:\n\n---\n\n## 1. `name_behavior_mismatch` (False Identity) — 3 findings\n\n| ID | File:lines | Symbol | Side-effect signals |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| crime_00032 | `src/index.ts:167-459` | `build` | `createLogger`, `removeFiles` (4 signals) |\n| crime_00049 | `src/rollup.ts:38-159` | `getRollupConfig` | `setSilent`, `removeFiles` (4 signals) |\n| crime_00054 | `src/index.ts:291-365` | `buildAll` | `removeFiles` (3 signals) |\n| crime_00072 | `src/rollup.ts:77-81` | `buildStart` | `removeFiles` (2 signals) |\n\n**What an agent gets wrong today.** A `get*` prefix is the universal \"this is a pure read\" convention. An agent extending `getRollupConfig` to add a new format will reasonably assume it can be called twice, called speculatively, or moved earlier in the boot sequence — and then it silently wipes the user's `outDir` (via `removeFiles`) and flips the logger into silent mode. Same trap for `build`/`buildAll`: the names sound like calculations, but they reach for the filesystem and the logger before doing any work.\n\n**Refactor proposals.**\n- `getRollupConfig` → split into `computeRollupConfig(options)` (pure, returns a config object) and `prepareRollupRun(options)` (does the `setSilent` + `removeFiles`, then calls `computeRollupConfig`). The callers in `src/rollup.ts` and `src/index.ts` migrate to whichever they actually need.\n- `buildStart` (the Rollup plugin hook) — this one is a forced rename only at the boundary: leave the hook itself, but pull `removeFiles` out into an explicit `cleanOutDir(...)` helper called from `prepareRollupRun`, so the hook becomes a one-liner that doesn't surprise.\n- `build` in `src/index.ts` is the public entry point of the package, so renaming is breaking. Instead: extract `runBuild` (does I/O) and keep `build` as a thin wrapper whose JSDoc explicitly documents the side effects (`removes files in outDir`, `creates a logger`). Then the False Identity finding goes away for the inner function, and the outer one has a contract written down.\n- `buildAll` → `runAllBuilds`. Internal, no callers outside this file (cross-check with fan-in finding crime_00046 — `src/index.ts` is fan-in 4, so a quick grep before renaming).\n\n---\n\n## 2. `option_bag_junk_drawer` — 1 finding in scope\n\n| ID | File:lines | Symbol | Property reads |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| crime_00053 | `src/rollup.ts:38-159` | `getRollupConfig(options)` | 10 fields: `cjsInterop, clean, dts, entry, external, format, outDir, outExtension, …` |\n\n(Two more `option_bag_junk_drawer` findings exist in `src/cli-main.ts` and `src/esbuild/index.ts` — out of scope for this task but worth flagging as the same shape.)\n\n**What an agent gets wrong today.** `options: any`-style bags mean the agent has to read the whole 122-line body to learn which fields are required vs optional vs ignored. They'll often **silently drop** an unrecognized field they meant to add (no compile error, no runtime error, just a quiet no-op), or pass through a `format` value the function doesn't actually support. The fact that this function shares a name and 7 of 10 fields with `runEsbuild`'s options bag (crime_00050) makes it worse — agents will assume they're interchangeable.\n\n**Refactor proposal.**\n- Define a named `RollupBuildOptions` interface (probably in `src/options.ts` or wherever `NormalizedOptions` lives) listing exactly the 10 fields read here, each typed and JSDoc'd. Destructure at the top: `const { cjsInterop, clean, dts, entry, external, format, outDir, outExtension, … } = options;`. That alone moves the contract from \"buried in 122 lines\" to \"visible in the signature.\"\n- If `RollupBuildOptions` turns out to be a strict subset of the package-wide `NormalizedOptions`, use `Pick<NormalizedOptions, …>` rather than a duplicate type — keeps the source of truth singular.\n\n---\n\n## 3. `return_shape_roulette` — 3 findings, all in `src/esbuild/svelte.ts`\n\n| ID | Symbol | Shapes | Example divergence |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| crime_00051 | `sveltePlugin` (9-124) | 6 | `{ args, namespace, path }` vs `{ location, text }` |\n| crime_00052 | `setup` (17-122) | 6 | (same — `setup` is the body of `sveltePlugin`) |\n| crime_00055 | `<anonymous>` (31-121) | 5 | `{ location, text }` vs `{ code }` |\n\nThese are nested: `sveltePlugin` wraps `setup`, which contains the anonymous esbuild `onLoad`/`onResolve` callbacks. The three findings are really one structural problem reported at three nesting levels.\n\n**What an agent gets wrong today.** Esbuild plugin callbacks have **strict, documented contracts** — `onResolve` returns `{ path, namespace, … } | null`, `onLoad` returns `{ contents, loader, … } | null`, error messages return `{ location, text }`. Today none of those branches have an explicit return type, so an agent adding a new code path (say, handling `.svelte.md`) can return `{ path, contents }` — a hybrid that compiles, satisfies inference, and then crashes inside esbuild with an unhelpful error. The 0% key overlap noted in the evidence is the giveaway: these aren't variants of one type, they're distinct contracts being smuggled through `any`.\n\n**Refactor proposal.**\n- Import the actual esbuild types: `import type { OnResolveResult, OnLoadResult, PartialMessage } from 'esbuild'`.\n- Annotate each callback's return type explicitly:\n  ```ts\n  build.onResolve({ filter: /\\.svelte$/ }, (args): OnResolveResult => { … });\n  build.onLoad({ filter: /\\.svelte$/, namespace: 'svelte' }, (args): OnLoadResult => { … });\n  ```\n  This is a 3-line change per callback that turns silent shape errors into compile errors.\n- Error-object returns (`{ location, text }`) should be typed as `PartialMessage[]` inside the `errors`/`warnings` arrays of `OnLoadResult`, not returned as a top-level shape — fixing the typing will likely expose one or two spots where errors are being returned at the wrong level.\n\n---\n\n## Suggested commit order\n\n1. **svelte.ts return types** (lowest risk, mechanical, kills 3 findings at once).\n2. **`RollupBuildOptions` named type** for `getRollupConfig` — additive, safe.\n3. **Rename `buildAll` → `runAllBuilds`** internally.\n4. **Extract `cleanOutDir`** from `getRollupConfig` / `buildStart` / `build` — once that's a named helper, the False Identity verdict on the surrounding functions weakens naturally because the side effect is now disclosed at the call site.\n5. **Leave the public `build` name alone**; document side effects via JSDoc + extract `runBuild` inner function.\n\nEach step is a separate commit with the corresponding crimes finding IDs in the message, so the next `crimes scan` cleanly shows which ones moved.",
