/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.8.1/claude/refactor-04-monorepo.json:7:  "response": "# Refactor plan — petty agent-risk in `src/index.ts`, `src/rollup.ts`, `src/esbuild/svelte.ts`\n\n## Findings in scope (8)\n\n**False Identity — `name_behavior_mismatch`**\n- `crime_00030` — `src/index.ts:167` `build` — name reads as pure transform, body calls `createLogger`, `removeFiles` (4 side-effect signals)\n- `crime_00057` — `src/index.ts:291` `buildAll` — calls `removeFiles` (3 signals)\n- `crime_00052` — `src/rollup.ts:38` `getRollupConfig` — `get*` reads as a pure accessor, body calls `setSilent`, `removeFiles` (4 signals)\n- `crime_00079` — `src/rollup.ts:77` `buildStart` — calls `removeFiles` (2 signals)\n\n**Option Bag Junk Drawer — `option_bag_junk_drawer`**\n- `crime_00056` — `src/rollup.ts:38` `getRollupConfig(options)` — 10 distinct property reads off a generic bag\n\n**Return Shape Roulette — `return_shape_roulette`**\n- `crime_00054` — `src/esbuild/svelte.ts:9` `sveltePlugin` — 6 object-literal return shapes, 0% key overlap\n- `crime_00055` — `src/esbuild/svelte.ts:17` `setup` — 6 shapes, 0% overlap\n- `crime_00062` — `src/esbuild/svelte.ts:31` anonymous handler — 5 shapes, 0% overlap\n\n---\n\n## What an agent can get wrong today\n\n### `src/rollup.ts` — `getRollupConfig`\nA `get*` name promises a read. Reality: it mutates the logger via `setSilent` *and* deletes the output directory via `removeFiles`. An agent looking to \"cache the config for watch mode\" or \"precompute config once at startup\" will silently double-delete `outDir` and stomp on logger state on the second call. The `options` bag amplifies the trap — the agent reading the signature sees `(options)` and has no way to know which of the 10 fields (`clean`, `outDir`, `silent`, …) drive the destructive paths.\n\n### `src/index.ts` — `build` / `buildAll`\nBoth are top-of-the-file orchestrators with safe-sounding names. An agent wrapping them in `Promise.all`, retry-with-backoff, or \"rebuild on file change\" assumes idempotence; the calls to `removeFiles` make them anything but. `build` is also the 293-line god function, so the side effects are buried far below the signature where an agent skimming the head of the file won't see them.\n\n### `src/esbuild/svelte.ts` — return shapes\nThe three plugin callbacks return six distinct object shapes with **zero key overlap** between branches: `{ path, namespace }` for resolve hits, `{ contents, loader }` for loads, `{ location, text }` for diagnostics, etc. Today they flow through inferred `any`. An agent adding a 7th branch (say, a watch-mode invalidation) has no type-driven signal for:\n- Which keys esbuild actually consumes in each callback context (esbuild silently ignores keys outside the expected shape).\n- Whether `errors` can be mixed with `{ contents, loader }` (it can — but the agent has to read the esbuild docs to discover that).\n- Which of the six existing shapes is the template for their new branch.\n\n---\n\n## Proposed refactor\n\n### Step 1 — type the option bag (`crime_00056`)\n\n`getRollupConfig` reads 10 fields. Introduce a `Pick`-derived type so the parameter is a checklist, not a junk drawer:\n\n```ts\ntype RollupConfigInput = Pick<NormalizedOptions,\n  | 'entry' | 'external' | 'format' | 'outDir' | 'outExtension'\n  | 'cjsInterop' | 'clean' | 'dts' | 'silent' /* … */>;\n```\n\n`Pick<NormalizedOptions, …>` beats a brand-new interface here: the canonical shape already exists upstream, so duplicating it would drift. Adding a new field becomes a deliberate edit to the `Pick` keys before the function can read it.\n\nZero behaviour change. Required precondition for steps 2 and 3 because once the type narrows, the side-effect extraction below has a clean signature to hand off to.\n\n### Step 2 — extract the side effects, then rename (`crime_00030/52/57/79`)\n\nDon't just rename — **split the pure read from the mutation**, then rename what's left:\n\n```ts\n// src/rollup.ts — before\nexport const getRollupConfig = async (options) => {\n  setSilent(options.silent)\n  await removeFiles(options.clean, options.outDir)\n  return { /* config */ }\n}\n\n// after\nconst buildRollupConfig = (options: RollupConfigInput): RollupConfig => { /* pure */ }\n\nconst prepareRollupOutput = async (options: RollupConfigInput): Promise<void> => {\n  setSilent(options.silent)\n  if (options.clean) await removeFiles(options.clean, options.outDir)\n}\n```\n\nRename map for the others:\n| Before | After | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| `build` (index.ts:167) | `runBuild` + `setupRunArtifacts(options)` | `run*` discloses effects; helper extracts the `createLogger` / `removeFiles` calls |\n| `buildAll` (index.ts:291) | `runAllBuilds` + `cleanBuildOutputs(options)` | Caller invokes the clean step explicitly |\n| `buildStart` (rollup.ts:77) | **keep** | Rollup plugin lifecycle hook — renaming breaks Rollup's contract. Add a one-line `// rollup hook — clears prior dist on each rebuild` comment instead |\n\nRule for the future: any function whose first call is `removeFiles` must either (a) say so in its name (`clean*`, `reset*`, `prepare*`) or (b) be a framework-required hook with a one-line comment.\n\n### Step 3 — name the return shapes (`crime_00054/55/62`)\n\nThe 6 distinct shapes map to **3 esbuild callback contracts**. Name them and let the union do the work:\n\n```ts\ntype SvelteResolveResult  = { path: string; namespace?: string; }\ntype SvelteLoadResult     = { contents: string; loader?: esbuild.Loader; }\ntype SvelteDiagnostic     = { errors?: PartialMessage[]; warnings?: PartialMessage[]; }\n\nbuild.onResolve({ filter }, (args): SvelteResolveResult | SvelteDiagnostic => { /* … */ })\nbuild.onLoad({ filter },    (args): SvelteLoadResult    | SvelteDiagnostic => { /* … */ })\n```\n\nSix freelance shapes collapse into three named contracts that match esbuild's own callback typing. An agent adding a 7th branch now gets a TS error if they mix keys across the union — the bug becomes a compile failure instead of a silently-ignored field. The anonymous handler at line 31 inherits the constraint from `setup`'s callback signature, no separate change needed.\n\n---\n\n## What's deliberately out of scope\n\n- **The God Functions** (crime_00003/04/05/08/14/15) — same files, but the prompt's \"petty agent-risk\" framing points at clarity, not size. Steps 1–3 are a precondition for splitting `build` safely: once the options bag is typed and the destructive ops are named, extracting helpers from the 293-line body stops being a guessing game about which helper owns `removeFiles`.\n- `Date.now()` in `rollup.ts` (crime_00012), boolean naming in `plugin.ts`, fan-out — different detector families, addressed by other scenarios.\n\n## Sequencing\n\n1. **Type the options bag** — zero-risk, unblocks the rest.\n2. **Extract + rename** — each function in its own commit; the type from step 1 catches misuse at compile time.\n3. **Annotate return shapes** — last because it touches the most callbacks and benefits from steady call sites above.\n\nEach step is independently mergeable; the type annotations are the safety net that keeps the renames from quietly breaking callers.",
