     <button\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n        type=\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"button\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n        onClick={onActivate}\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n        className=\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"w-full max-w-2xl bg-brand-accent text-ink-900\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n      >\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n        {children}\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n      </button>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n    );\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  }\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  return (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n    <div className=\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"w-full max-w-2xl bg-brand-accent text-ink-900\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\">\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n      {children}\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n    </div>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  );\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n}\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n```\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n### Each change tied to its finding type\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n1. **Accessibility (`accessible_interaction_risk`, crime_00001, line 7)** — The `<div onClick>` is replaced with a real `<button type=\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"button\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\">` when the card is interactive, and the click handler is hoisted to an `onActivate` prop. A button is reachable by Tab, activatable by Enter/Space, and announced as a button by screen readers — no `role`/`tabIndex`/`aria-label` workarounds needed. When the card is non-interactive (no `onActivate`), it stays a `<div>` with no click handler at all, which is the safer default than leaving a fake button behind. The suggested action in the finding (`switch_to_button_or_add_aria`) recommends exactly this swap; preferring the real element over `role=\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"button\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"` avoids re-implementing keyboard semantics by hand.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n2. **Design-token escape (hex literals in inline `style`)** — `#ff00aa` and `#0a0a0a` are inlined hex values that bypass the design system: they can't be themed, can't be audited for contrast, and won't track palette changes. They're replaced with Tailwind utility classes that resolve to named tokens (`bg-brand-accent`, `text-ink-900`). The exact token names depend on the project's `tailwind.config.*`; if those keys don't exist yet, add them there rather than re-inlining hex. Inline `style` is also dropped entirely, which removes the per-render style object allocation as a small bonus.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n3. **Responsive fragility (fixed `width: 800`)** — A hard-coded 800px width overflows any viewport under 800px and refuses to grow on larger ones. It's replaced with `w-full max-w-2xl` so the card fills its container by default and caps at roughly the same visual width on wide screens (`max-w-2xl` ≈ 672px; pick `max-w-3xl` or define a custom `max-w-card` token if you want closer to 800). This makes the component work inside any layout slot without the parent having to clamp it.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n### Suggested follow-ups (out of scope for this fixture but worth flagging)\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Add a snapshot/RTL test that asserts the rendered element is a `<button>` when `onActivate` is provided — this would close the `test_gap: 1.00` score on the existing finding.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- If you want the design-token escape and fixed-pixel-width to actually show up in future scans, those would be new detectors in `packages/language-js` (e.g. `style_token_escape`, `fixed_pixel_layout`) feeding into `core`'s finding schema — they fit cleanly under the \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"frontend agent-risk\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" theme alongside `accessible_interaction_risk`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\\n/Users/andrew/dev/crimes/evals/results/0.7.0/claude/refactor-07-stress-frontend.json:14:        \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"expected\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"design_token_escape\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\\n/Users/andrew/dev/crimes/evals/results/0.7.0/claude/refactor-07-stress-frontend.json:20:        \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"expected\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"accessible_intera