outes + docs. Pick canonical vocabulary before the next route lands. |\\\\n| crime_00013 | Unfinished Business | `src/todo.ts` 14 markers | 0.40 / 0.57 | Whole file is half-built. Either land it or delete it. |\\\\n| crime_00003 | Commented-Out Corpse | `src/billing.ts:33-37` | 0.45 / 0.53 | Stale `legacyRefund` snippet in billing — delete or annotate. Trivial. |\\\\n| crime_00002 | Missing Agent Context | repo root | 0.60 / 0.61 | No `AGENTS.md`/`CLAUDE.md`/skills, undeclared `bin: messy`. Repo-wide concern, not PR-shaped — call out as a parallel task rather than holding the PR. |\\\\n| crime_00020 | Unfinished Business | `src/billing.ts` 4 markers | 0.20 / 0.40 | Borderline — listing here because the file is already in scope for the blockers. |\\\\n\\\\n## Ignore (8)\\\\n\\\\nLow severity + low/medium agent_risk in non-load-bearing surfaces. Note, don't block.\\\\n\\\\n| id | charge | file | sev / ar | why |\\\\n|---|---|---|---|---|\\\\n| crime_00015 | Docs-Code Drift | `docs/teams.md` → `./setup.md` | 0.35 / 0.51 | Doc-only broken link. |\\\\n| crime_00016 | Test That Proves Nothing | `src/billing.test.ts:8-10` \\\\\\\"creates an invoice\\\\\\\" | 0.25 / 0.34 | Weak matcher only — fold into the test-quality follow-up implied by crime_00006. |\\\\n| crime_00017 | Option Bag Junk Drawer | `describeCheckout` | 0.30 / 0.48 | Local clarity issue, `petty.ts` is aptly named. |\\\\n| crime_00018 | Return Shape Roulette | `resolvePaymentResult` | 0.30 / 0.48 | Same. |\\\\n| crime_00019 | Negative Flag Maze | `src/petty.ts:35` | 0.25 / 0.47 | Two-flag double-negative, mechanically simple. |\\\\n| crime_00021 | Orphaned Destination | `/account/subscription` | 0.40 / 0.46 | Likely in-flight; pairs with the tenant alias drift (crime_00009) — wait until vocabulary is decided. |\\\\n| crime_00022 | Orphaned Destination | `/team` | 0.40 / 0.46 | Same. |\\\\n| crime_00023 | Orphaned Destination | `/workspace/members` | 0.40 / 0.46 | Same. |\\\\n\\\\n## Threading the findings together\\\\n\\\\nThe three blockers, the two billing-test warnings, and the God File all sit in `src/billing.ts`. They are one cluster, not six unrelated issues — a single follow-up that injects a clock, encodes the owner/refund rule, renames `calculateRefundPreview`, and splits the file would clear most of the medium-severity surface in billing at once.\\\\n\\\\nThe nav/route/alias warnings (crime_00007/00009/00012/00014 + the three orphans) are the other cluster — same destination labelled inconsistently while three sibling routes float unlinked. Resolve the canonical vocabulary first, then the orphans either get linked or deleted.\\\",\\n/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.1/claude/review-01-messy-ts-app.json:14:      \\\"crime_00006\\\": \\\"weak_test_signal\\\",\\n/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.1/claude/review-01-messy-ts-app.json:24:      \\\"crime_00016\\\": \\\"weak_test_signal\\\",\\n/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.1/claude/review-01-messy-ts-app.json:37:      \\\"Test That Proves Nothing\\\": \\\"weak_test_signal\\\",\\n/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.1/claude/refactor-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  \\\"response\\\": \\\"# Top 3 changes to `src/billing.ts`\\\\n\\\\n## 1. Fix `calculateRefundPreview` — name lies about behavior\\\\n**Finding:** `crime_00008` (False Identity, lines 40–44, agent_risk 0.52)\\\\n\\\\nThe name reads as a pure calculation, but the body calls `saveRefundAudit` and `sendRefundEmail`. Any caller — human or agent — that treats this as safe to invoke speculatively will trigger real-world side effects. Highest-value fix because the misleading name is *actively* dangerous, not just messy.\\\\n\\\\n- Split into `calculateRefundPreview` (pure) + `recordAndNotifyRefund` (side effects), or\\\\n- Rename to `previewAndAuditRefund` so the audit/email work is disclosed in the signature.\\\\n\\\\n## 2. Move the refund authorization rule out of comments\\\\n**Findings:** `crime_00011` (Logic in the Alibi, line 39) + `crime_00003` (Commented-Out Corpse, lines 33–37)\\\\n\\\\nThe comment at line 39 carries a load-bearing policy (\\\\\\\"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves\\\\\\\") that the scanner couldn't see encoded in nearby code — meaning it likely *isn't* enforced, or is enforced somewhere non-obvious. Adjacent to it is a block of disabled code (`const legacyRefund = await loadRefund(user.id);`) that invites an agent to \\\\\\\"restore\\\\\\\" stale behavior.\\\\n\\\\n- Encode the rule as a named guard, e.g. `assertCanRefund(user, plan)`, and put a test on it.\\\\n- Delete the commented-out legacy refund block outright; if there's a reason to remember it, replace it with one line of rationale.\\\\n\\\\nThese two are tightly co-located (lines 33–44) and clean up the whole refund entry surface together.\\\\n\\\\n## 3. Inject a clock to kill Temporal Recklessness\\\\n**Finding:** `crime_00004` (Temporal Recklessness, 7 calls on lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273, agent_risk 0.53)\\\\n\\\\nSeven direct reads of wall time spread across the file mean nothing in `billing.ts` can be pinned in a test without monkey-patching `Date`. Given the file already has a `Test That Proves Nothing` (`crime_00006`) and a weak `creates an invoice` test (`crime_00016`), the test debt isn't going to shrink until time is injectable.\\\\n\\\\n- Add a `Clock` interface (`now(): number`) and default it to `() => Date.now()` at the module edge.\\\\n- Replace each call site; the tests for the refund authorization rule from #2 become trivial once `now()` is mockable.\\\\n\\\\n---\\\\n\\\\n**Why these three, in this order:** #1 stops the file from quietly causing side effects under a safe-sounding name. #2 turns a prose rule into enforceable code right where the riskiest function lives. #3 unlocks the testing that lets you verify #1 and #2 didn't regress anything. The God File (`crime_00010`) and TODO density (`crime_00020`) findings will largely dissolve once the refund flow is extracted.\\\",\\n/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.1/claude/refactor-01-messy-ts-app.json:14:      \\\"crime_00006\\\": \\\"weak_test_signal\\\",\\n/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.1/claude/refactor-01-messy-ts-app.json:24:      \\\"crime_00016\\\": \\\"weak_test_signal\\\",\\n/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.1/claude/refactor-01-messy-ts-app.json:37:      \\\"Test That Proves Nothing\\\": \\\"weak_test_signal\\\",\\n/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.1/claude/plan-01-messy-ts-app.json:14:      \\\"crime_00006\\\": \\\"weak_test_signal\\\",\\n/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.1/claude/plan-01-messy-ts-app.json:24:      \\\"crime_00016\\\": \\\"weak_test_signal\\\",\\n/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.1/claude/plan-01-messy-ts-app.json:37:      \\\"Test That Proves Nothing\\\": \\\"weak_test_signal\\\",\\n/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.1/claude/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:14:      \\\"crime_00006\\\": \\\"weak_test_signal\\\",\\n/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.1/claude/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:24:      \\\"crime_00016\\\": \\\"weak_test_signal\\\",\\n/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.1/claude/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:37:      \\\"Test That Proves Nothing\\\": \\\"weak_test_signal\\\",\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_11\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/zsh -lc \\\"find /Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a -path '*04-monorepo*' -print\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_12\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/zsh -lc \\\"find /Users/andrew/dev -maxdepth 4 -iname '*tsup*' -o -iname '*04-monorepo*'\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":n