ostic type used by the installed version.\\n- Split callback bodies by contract:\\n  - `resolveSvelteImport(args): OnResolveResult`\\n  - `loadSvelteFile(args): Promise<OnLoadResult>`\\n  - `formatSvelteCompileError(error): PartialMessage`\\n  - `compileSvelteToJavaScript(source, filename): SvelteCompileResult`\\n- Name intermediate result variants instead of returning raw object literals from every branch.\\n- Keep `sveltePlugin(options): Plugin` as a thin adapter that wires esbuild hooks to those helpers.\\n\\n**Large Function / Large File**\\n\\nFindings:\\n- `src/index.ts`: `build`, anonymous build body, `mainTasks`, `normalizeOptions`, `buildAll`, `startWatcher`; file is also over the large-file threshold.\\n- `src/rollup.ts`: `getRollupConfig`\\n- `src/esbuild/svelte.ts`: `sveltePlugin`, `setup`, anonymous callback\\n\\nRisk today:\\nAn agent making a small behavior change has to keep too many invariants in working memory: cleaning, watch mode, entry normalization, DTS behavior, plugin setup, output config, and logging are interleaved.\\n\\nRefactor plan:\\n- `src/index.ts`\\n  - Extract `normalizeEntryOptions`, `normalizeDtsOptions`, `resolveOutDir`, `createBuildPlan`.\\n  - Split execution into `runOneTimeBuild(plan)` and `runWatchBuild(plan)`.\\n  - Keep exported `build(...)` as compatibility wrapper if public API stability matters, but make it delegate to `runBuild`.\\n- `src/rollup.ts`\\n  - Extract output creation, plugin list construction, declaration handling, and pre-build cleanup.\\n  - Keep Rollup hook objects small and move hook effects into named helpers.\\n- `src/esbuild/svelte.ts`\\n  - Keep `sveltePlugin` as declarative setup only.\\n  - Move resolve/load/compile/diagnostic behavior into typed helpers.\\n\\n**Order I’d Do It**\\n\\n1. Add named types first, without behavior changes.\\n2. Extract pure helpers from `src/esbuild/svelte.ts`, because explicit return types will catch contract drift quickly.\\n3. Split `src/rollup.ts` into pure config