/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.15/claude/context-04-monorepo.json:7:  "response": "## Agent context: missing\n\n`crimes scan` flagged it as `crime_00009` — **Missing Agent Context** (medium severity, confidence 0.9, agent_risk 0.61):\n\n- No `AGENTS.md` at repo root\n- No `CLAUDE.md` at repo root\n- No `.claude/skills/*/SKILL.md`\n- `package.json` declares bins (`tsup`, `tsup-node`) that an agent has no way to discover\n\n### Consequence for future agent work\n\nAn agent landing in this repo has to infer everything from source: which command builds, which tests to run, which files are load-bearing, and which conventions to follow. The scan already shows the trap door — `src/index.ts` (fan-out 17, 459 lines, `build` is 293 lines), `src/plugin.ts` (fan-in 10), and `src/utils.ts` (fan-in 18) are all hubs where a confident-but-wrong edit ripples widely. Without a context file, an agent won't know to treat them as load-bearing, won't know that `pnpm build` runs tsup, and won't know that the test suite has known weak-signal tests it shouldn't mimic.\n\n### Minimal `AGENTS.md` skeleton to clear the finding\n\n```markdown\n# AGENTS.md\n\nGuidance for coding agents working in this repo.\n\n## What this is\ntsup — a TypeScript bundler powered by esbuild. The `tsup` and `tsup-node` binaries are the product.\n\n## Commands\n- Install: `pnpm install`\n- Build: `pnpm build` (runs tsup on itself)\n- Test: `pnpm test` (Vitest)\n- Lint/typecheck: `pnpm lint` / `pnpm typecheck`\n\n## Layout\n- `src/index.ts` — public API + `build` orchestrator (load-bearing; high fan-out)\n- `src/plugin.ts` — rollup-style plugin pipeline (load-bearing; high fan-in)\n- `src/esbuild/` — esbuild integration and bundled plugins\n- `src/rollup.ts`, `src/rollup/` — `.d.ts` bundling via rollup\n- `src/utils.ts` — shared helpers (high fan-in; prefer additive changes)\n- `test/` — Vitest integration tests; many use file-system fixtures\n\n## Conventions\n- TypeScript strict; no `any` in 