p above so the hook body becomes a no-op or a logger nudge.\n\nNet: the prefix tells the truth, and the two side effects (`clean` + `silence`) become one named lifecycle call you can find with grep.\n\n## 2. Option Bag Junk Drawer — `options` parameters with implicit shapes\n\n| ID | Symbol | File | Distinct reads |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| crime_00056 | `getRollupConfig` | `src/rollup.ts:38–159` | 10 (`cjsInterop`, `clean`, `dts`, `entry`, `external`, `format`, `outDir`, `outExtension`, …) |\n\n**What an agent gets wrong today:** `options` is typed broadly (likely the union `NormalizedOptions` or `Options`), so reading a field that doesn't exist on the relevant variant compiles. An agent adding `options.someNewFlag` has no signal that callers have actually populated it; an agent adding a required field to the type silently breaks every call site that didn't go through `normalizeOptions`.\n\n**Proposal:**\n- Introduce a `RollupConfigInputs` named type with exactly the 10 fields read, derived from `NormalizedOptions` via `Pick<>`. Signature becomes `resolveRollupConfig(inputs: RollupConfigInputs)`.\n- Destructure at the parameter — `({ cjsInterop, clean, dts, entry, … }: RollupConfigInputs)` — so unused fields become a deletion candidate, not silent overpassing.\n- Side benefit: the new type doubles as the contract for the eventual extraction out of `src/index.ts`'s `build`, where these same fields are computed.\n\n(The same pattern applies to `runEsbuild` and `main` in other files — flagging here but explicitly deferred per scenario scope.)\n\n## 3. Return Shape Roulette — `src/esbuild/svelte.ts` returning unrelated shapes\n\n| ID | Symbol | Lines | Shapes | Example keys |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| crime_00054 | `sveltePlugin` | 9–124 | 6, 0% min overlap | `{ args, namespace, path }` vs `{ location, text }` |\n| crime_00055 | `setup` (class method) | 17–122 | 6, 0% min overlap | same |\n| crime_00062 | `<anonymous>` callback | 31–121 | 5, 0% min overlap | `{ location, text }` vs `{ code }` |\n\nThese three are the same function nest: `sveltePlugin` is the factory, `setup` is its body, and the anonymous arrow is the `onLoad` / `onResolve` callback inside `setup`. The 6 shapes are esbuild's plugin protocol — different callbacks return different result types (resolved path vs load result vs error), but the file has no explicit return annotations, so TS infers a union.\n\n**What an agent gets wrong today:** the inferred union widens silently each time you add a branch. An agent adding a new error path that returns `{ message }` instead of `{ text }` won't get a TS error at the return site — they'll only see it when esbuild fails to display the diagnostic at runtime. Worse, the `{ location, text }` shape is esbuild's `PartialMessage` and `{ args, namespace, path }` is `OnResolveResult`; mixing them in one inferred return type means the agent has no signal which callback they're inside.\n\n**Proposal:**\n- Annotate each callback with its esbuild type explicitly: the `onResolve` arrow returns `OnResolveResult | null | undefined`, the `onLoad` arrow returns `OnLoadResult | null | undefined`. These types ship with `esbuild`.\n- Annotate `setup`'s return as `void` (esbuild plugins' `setup` is void-returning by contract).\n- Annotate `sveltePlugin`'s return as `Plugin` from esbuild.\n\nNo structural refactor needed — this is purely \"type the seams\". After this, the inferred-union noise disappears and the detector goes quiet.\n\n## Ordering and risk\n\n1. **First**: the svelte.ts type annotations (lowest risk — pure additions, can ship as one commit).\n2. **Second**: `getRollupConfig → resolveRollupConfig` + `RollupConfigInputs` (one file, one signature, callers compile-checked).\n3. **Third**: extract `prepareRollupSession` and rename `build → runBuild` (touches `src/index.ts`'s `build` orchestrator and `src/rollup.ts`'s `buildStart`; needs a coordinated commit because the side effects move).\n\nNone of these require touching the god-func